Then let the iron be lowered a second time into the vessel containing the spirit of nitre, that action may be excited anew. But that this may the better succeed, an ample supply of spirit ol uitre ought to be put into the vessel, or rather two vessels containing spirit olnitre, and also two small portioris ol iron, should be suspended in the glass. When the water sinks anew about five finger-breadths in consequence of the vapours produced, let the iron as before be taken out ol the vessel, and when this is done the water will gradually rise in the glasS, yet not so quickly nor so far as the first time. For the water which rose after the first action about six finger- breadthS, aud far indeed above the height first marked, will only rise after the second, even should it be more intense, some two finger-breadths more or less. Nay, it will never rise to the mark from which it fell. If the action be repeated a third time the result will be just the same as in the second,
